In OSGi there is no way to get the your Bundle object until after you are 
passed your BundleContext in the BundleActivator.start(BundleContext) method.  
You should be overriding the start(BundleContext) method of AbstractUIPlugin 
and doing your work there like this:

public void start(BundleContext context) throws Exception {
	super.start(context);
	Bundle b = getBundle();
	IDialogSettings settings = getDialogSettings();
}

The start(BundleContext) method will be called right after your plugin class 
is constructed and will only be called once during the active lifecycle of 
your bundle.  So you should be able to do what you need in there.

The Plugin and AbstractUIPlugin Classes could be improved to throw 
IllegalStateExceptions when (bundle == null).  For example in Plugin:

public final IPath getStateLocation() throws IllegalStateException {
  if (bundle == null)
    throw new IllegalStateException();
  return InternalPlatform.getDefault().getStateLocation(bundle, true);
}

There are several methods in Plugin that access the bundle object.  The checks 
could be done to prevent NPE's.  But we would really just be trading one 
RuntimeException for another cleaner more correct one.  You would still not be 
able to call these methods from your Plugin constructor.
